https://prez.dev/description.@value:
Terms used to describe the stage of metamorphism of rocks based on the nature of the change in pressure and temperature conditions to which the rocks are subjected. Definitions are taken or derived from:
Fettes, D and Desmons, J (eds.) 2007, Metamorphic Rocks: a classification and glossary of terms — Recommendations of the International Union of Geological Sciences Subcommission on the Systematics of Metamorphic Rocks: Cambridge University Press, 244p.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#defi.@value: Typically reserved for use when: a) overprinting or unclear spatial–textural relationships do not allow discernment of whether all or some of the minerals preserved in the rock are indicative of the highest temperature equilibrium mineral assemblage; or b) the possibility of polymetamorphism is likely. This ambiguity arises, for example, when sluggish reaction kinetics in porphyroblastic minerals at low to moderate pressure/temperature metamorphic conditions lead to metastability.
